= Form Follows Function

A saying from the 20#super("th") century bauhaus movement that valued function over ornament. An idea that in some respects was just a secular rediscovery of 19#super("th") century Shaker theology that rejected ornament and status signaling. However, in some ways the Shakers were even more rigid than 20#super("th") century design philosophy.

#align(center)[
  #quote[Don't make something unless it is both necessary and useful.]
]

In modernism: many chair designs; many interpretations of #quote[minimal] style differences between designers; ego imbued in the artifact. While for the Shakers however: the individual does not have authority to redesign objects freely; craft must carry no personal signature, no stylistic identity nor shall the object reveal the maker. Even major Shaker innovations were never patented (a detail that complicates historical attribution).

== Does form follow function?

#form-follows-function-comparison()

=== No! Form does not follow function

Conventional LEDs as implemented today violate the rule that form shall follow function and the result has been widespread consumer distaste yet there is no physical reason why consumers should dislike LEDs, it's an engineering problem. Manufacturers retrofitted a new technology onto old the architecture, violating the rule. 

Obviously: why should LEDs mimic the Edison bulb? 

Less obvious: the electrical circuitry required to rectify AC power as well constant current regulation necessary to restrain thermal instability inherent to LEDs. Such complexity that is hidden rather than honestly expressed: violating the Shaker preference for structural truth. 

Consider dimming LEDs: light emission is a function of current not voltage and therefore dimming is a function of current. 

In contrast the physics inherent to the glowing filament of incandescent lamps has two beneficial effects: 
- As the filament gets hotter resistance increases; incandescent lamps are self stabilizing.
- Stored thermal energy in the glowing filament smooths out any ripples in current waveform. This is why we don't notice our lights dimming in tandem with the oscillating frequency of AC (zero twice per period).

Conversely:
- Ripples in LED current will transform to ripples in light emission.
- As the light emitting diodes themselves get hotter: resistance decreases; current increases; all in a positive feedback loop aka thermal runaway.

Moreover, solid state lighting has unique advantages that are lost when retrofitted onto the old architecture. Once this is recognized, it makes more sense to rethink lighting around this new technology. Moreover at some point all new homes, commercial spaces will likely be DC native in their electrical wiring. These DC native buildings will be maximally efficient with regard to the utilization of renewable energy and stored battery power.

The first step from here to there will likely begin with low voltage DC wiring for interior lighting. 

A new professional class will be needed. The current labor pool is insufficient. Here I'm particularly optimistic. Did you know that when I was 17 (or somewhere thereabout) I worked as a data center tech? I was essentially a low voltage tech, and while I hardly understood what I was doing, noting burned down. This is because Class 2 Low Voltage Wiring as defined by the NEC is touch safe, fire safe, and as a consequence is free from traditional electrical regulations. You do not need to be a licensed electrician to install class 2 low voltage electrical systems just as you don't need to be an electrician to run low voltage ethernet cabling. 

Here, the utility of low voltage DC native lighting has hardly been realized:
- Lower labor costs.
- Lower material costs, reduction in copper is most significant up to 75% according to #link("https://atx-led.com/blogs/news/the-build-series-energy-star-zerh-and-high-efficient-lighting-48v-dc-led-s")[this report].

The convergence of desirable qualities is interesting. With low barriers to entry, labor is a solvable problem. What's left are design, architectural questions. As an emerging market, innovation blossoms in low regulatory environments. 
